===Etymology===
Recorded since 1579, from two virtual synonyms: obsolete [[quag]] "bog, marsh" (a variant of {{etyl|enm}} [[quabbe]] "a marsh, bog", from {{etyl|ang}} *cwabba "shake, tremble" like something soft and flabby; cognate with Dutch [[kwab]]) + [[mire]] (from {{etyl|enm}}, from {{etyl|ono}} mȲyrr, akin to Old English [[mōs]] 'marsh' and [[moss]]). The sense "difficult situation, inextricable position" is recorded since 1775

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈkwɒg.maɪə(ɹ)/}} {{SAMPA|/"kwQg.maI@(r)/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[swampy]], [[soggy]] area of [[ground]].
#:''That '''quagmire''' regularly 'swallows' caught-up hikers' boots
# {{figurative}} A [[perilous]], mixed up and troubled situation; a hopeless [[tangle]]; a [[predicament]].
#:''The paperwork got lost in a '''quagmire''' of bureaucracy.''
#:''Those election results are a '''quagmire''' for any coalition except one of national union

